Introduction:¶

According to the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics, housing was the largest share of annual expenditures in 2022 at 33.3% alongside transportation the second largest share at 16.8%. This implies that both housing and transportation play a critical role in determining the costs faced by individual Americans households. However, while expenditures are important, time is also crucially important, and traffic is a massive time waster with roughly 59 hours wasted per person each year in Baltimore alone.

This project will attempt to answer some questions regarding traffic including the relationship between the cost of residential areas in each area and the traffic-related metrics recorded. Also, the traffic-based differences in each area based on whether they are rural or urban will also be evaluated. Then, a model will be constructed to show whether we can successfully predict traffic-related metrics in each area based on the housing costs near it.

Traffic will be analyzed by the following metrics:

1.) AADT (Annual Average Daily Traffic) is a traffic metric which measures the average number of vehicles going through a specific area over the course of a year.

2.) K-Factor which measures how much of daily traffic occurs at the peak hour of traffic. Is good for analyzing how bad the traffic is on average at peak times compared to the rest of the day.

Cost of residential areas will be caluclated with the following metrics:

1.) Residential prices: The average price of properties sold off in given area.

2.) Appraised value: The amound of money a property is estimated to be at by a real-estate agent or someone with expertise. This differs from its actual value which is the price the property is sold at.

Sources:¶

The main source that will be utilized for this project is MDOT SHA Annual Average Daily Traffic (AADT) which is segmented by points which document the observed AADT at their respective road location. This source is the main dataset which contains the data that we want to predict for the machine learning section on whether residential prices nearby have a mathematical relationship with nearby traffic. Also, this source contains both AADT and K-Factor metrics and has an X-Y coordinate system that can be converted into a longitude-latitude metric.

The second source for the project is 2021 Total Sales by House Types by Zip Code which contains information on residential sales in Maryland by zip code. This source exists to provide a more condensed dataset in comparison to the third dataset/source which has each individual housing unit and its price in Maryland listed. It will be used in the machine learning section and explanatory section to show the general trend between housing property values and traffic in each area.

The final source is Maryland Property Data which is a large dataset (more than 2,000,000 rows) of properties in Maryland and their characteristics including owners, size, type, and monetary appraisal. This source will also have X-Y coordinates which will be converted to a latitude-longitude metric allowing it to be merged with the first dataset.

Furthermore, the first two sources have data related/based in 2021 hence allowing for the data to be analyzed in conjunction with each other. However, the third dataset has property values of 2022-2023 which is still close to 2021 but may add confounding variables to any data analysis/machine learning due to changes that could have occurred within two to three years. 2021 was chosen as the year for data analysis since it is the closest to current day and the effects of COVID-19 had begun to wear off that year (i.e. people went back to their jobs and traffic loads stabilized).

Now that we have analyzed the relationship between the two traffic metrics we want to further analyze the differences between urban and rural areas based on the percentage of cars contributing to AADT.

Two-Sample T-Test involving the ratio of AADT contribution by cars in Rural vs Urban areas.

Two-Sample T-Test First we create a new column Ratio which is the AADT of cars over the total AADT in 2021. This leads to our hypothesis test of seeing whether rural and urban areas have distinct ratios; however, outliers that are two standards deviations away from the two samples are removed.

Null hypothesis: The ratio between the Annual Average Daily Traffic (AADT) of cars over the total AADT in 2021 is the same for areas which are urban and rural in Maryland.

Alternative Hypothesis: The ratio between the Annual Average Daily Traffic (AADT) of cars over the total AADT in 2021 differs based on areas which are rural compared to urban in Maryland.

In [34]:
# The Ratio category is created here
test1 = df1[['AADT Car', 'Rural / Urban', 'County Name', 'AADT (Current)']].dropna()
test1['Ratio'] = test1['AADT Car']/test1['AADT (Current)']
# Samples are established and testing whether there are any serious outliers
sample1 = test1[test1['Rural / Urban'] == 'Urban']
sample2 = test1[test1['Rural / Urban'] == 'Rural']
print(sample1['Ratio'].describe())
print(sample2['Ratio'].describe())
print("\n")
# Based on the two statements above the outliers should be removed by 3 standard deviations.
cutoff1 = (3 * sample1['Ratio'].std())
cutoff2 = (3 * sample2['Ratio'].std())
sample1 = sample1[(sample1['Ratio'] > sample1['Ratio'].mean() - cutoff1) & (sample1['Ratio'] < sample1['Ratio'].mean() + cutoff1)]
sample2 = sample2[(sample2['Ratio'] > sample2['Ratio'].mean() - cutoff2) & (sample2['Ratio'] < sample2['Ratio'].mean() + cutoff2)]

Prelude to Machine Learning Model:

Now, for further analysis we want to get a general idea of the relationship (broad) between AADT and the relative residential property values in each area. To do this first we convert each zip code in the second dataset to longitude-latitude coordinates and then by a linear transformation X-Y coordinates, the metric used by ARCGIS. We approximated this linear metric using ARCGIS and calculating a line between two random points in the X-Y metric alongside there corresponding longitude and latitude values. The line correctly projects other random points (tested about two-three random points) hence it assumed this transformation applies uniformly throughout the entire dataset.

Machine Learning Models (Linear Regression):¶

Here we first apply unsupervised KNN clustering on the data points by first condensing the million or so datapoints by a wide margin and extroplating them to the datapoints in the first dataset. However, first we need to scale the appraised value down to a small number since we want to apply KNN to the data based on the X-Y coordinates with a very small influence of appraised value for edge cases. This is done since Also, the property type column is removed since it is no longer needed and the data is adjusted for any outliers for the appraised value. The outliers must be removed since they can wildly modify the appraised value for extrapolated datapoints.

Now, apply the KNN unsupervised nearest neigbors algorithm on the 3rd dataset and then take the appraised value mean of nearest neighbors for each point in dataset 2 as it's appraised value. Note, the purpose of this is to attach a value to the extrapolation points of the first dataset based on the relative appraisal values nearby (X-Y coordinates). In other words, I have made the points X-Y of the first dataset a centroid where the closest values near it in dataset 3 have their appraised values averaged. Three values of n_neighbors are chosen so we can observe the rough optimal number of neighbors needed to reduce the linear models Mean-Squared Error. They are above twenty since if any lower it may cause overfit to the data and more than 100 is computationally inefficent (2+ minutes running this block of code).

In [27]:
import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

index = 0
MSE = []
# Create the subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(20, 5))
# Begin to construct the Linear Regression models and their errors based on how many neighbors are used to construct it
for idx in [20, 50, 100]:
  X = []
  # test3 is a sanitized version of df1 with all the outliers removed.
  ext_pts = test3[['x','y']]
  ext_pts = ext_pts.rename(columns = {"y":"Y", "x": "X"})
  ext_pts['NFMTTLVL'] = (df3['NFMTTLVL'].mean())
  knn = NearestNeighbors(n_neighbors=idx, algorithm='ball_tree').fit(df3)
  not_needed, indices = knn.kneighbors(ext_pts)
  for x in indices:
    z1 = 0
    idxx = 0
    for e1 in x:
      z1 = z1 + df3.iloc[e1][2]
      idxx = idxx + 1
    X.append(z1/idxx)
  Y = test3['AADT 2021']
  # Now we apply Linear regression by first splitting test and training data.
  X = np.array(X).reshape(-1,1)
  X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X,Y,test_size = 0.2)
  # Now train the model and test it through prediction
  model = (LinearRegression()).fit(X_train, Y_train)
  pred = model.predict(X_test)
  MSE.append(mean_squared_error(Y_test, pred))
  axes[index].plot(X_train, model.predict(X_train), color='green', label='Linear Regression')
  # Plot the linear dataset
  axes[index].scatter(X_train, Y_train, color='blue', label='Train', alpha=0.5)
  axes[index].scatter(X_test, Y_test, color='red', label='Test', alpha=0.5)
  axes[index].set_title('Linear Rel. between AADT and Appraised value')
  axes[index].set_xlabel('Scaled appraised value of residential property')
  axes[index].set_ylabel('AADT 2021')
  axes[index].legend()
  index = index + 1


plt.show()

Based on the plots above it's safe to assume that our model has failed to predict AADT based off of appraisal value alone with any of the number of selected neighbors . However, the model does capture the slight positive linear relationship seen in the dataset.

index = 0
MSE2 = []
# Create the subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 4, figsize=(20, 5))
# Begin to construct the Linear Regression models and their errors based on how many neighbors are used to construct it
for idx in [20, 50, 100]:
  X = []
  # test3 is a sanitized version of df1 with all the outliers removed.
  ext_pts = test3[['x','y']]
  ext_pts = ext_pts.rename(columns = {"y":"Y", "x": "X"})
  ext_pts['NFMTTLVL'] = (df3['NFMTTLVL'].mean())
  knn = NearestNeighbors(n_neighbors=idx, algorithm='ball_tree').fit(df3)
  not_needed, indices = knn.kneighbors(ext_pts)
  for x in indices:
    z1 = 0
    idxx = 0
    for e1 in x:
      z1 = z1 + df3.iloc[e1][2]
      idxx = idxx + 1
    X.append(z1/idxx)
  Y = test3['K-Factor']
  # Now we apply Linear regression by first splitting test and training data.
  X = np.array(X).reshape(-1,1)
  X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X,Y,test_size = 0.2)
  # Now train the model and test it through prediction
  model = (LinearRegression()).fit(X_train, Y_train)
  pred = model.predict(X_test)
  MSE2.append(mean_squared_error(Y_test, pred))
  axes[index].plot(X_train, model.predict(X_train), color='green', label='Linear Regression')
  # Plot the linear dataset
  axes[index].scatter(X_train, Y_train, color='blue', label='Train', alpha=0.5)
  axes[index].scatter(X_test, Y_test, color='red', label='Test', alpha=0.5)
  axes[index].set_title('Linear Rel. between K-Factor and Appraised value')
  axes[index].set_xlabel('Scaled appraised value of residential property')
  axes[index].set_ylabel('K-Factor')
  axes[index].legend()
  index = index + 1

Conclusion:¶

Based on the results of the model, we can conclude that there is a slight positive linear relationship between both K-Factor and AADT with residential property values in the area. In other words, that implies that if you live in an area that is generally more expensive then your chances of experiencing peak traffic hours which are long and more traffic is marginally higher. Note, while there is correlation, it is not enough to prove causation and the both models in the machine learning section failed to predict accurately as the data has a more oval-spatial type appearance.

The model created might be more accurate with different metrics using gradient descent; however, the main purpose of this project was not to construct a model but rather detail the relationship between two factors which are rarely evaluated together. The residential pricing was interpolated onto the first dataset containing the traffic metric by utilizing unsupervised KNN. This carried some risks if the values of N=neighbors were not the right amount leading to potential overfitting if too small and underfitting if too small.

Furthermore, through exploratory analysis we found a pattern between the two traffic metrics, distinct characteristics of traffic-related data in this case the contribution percentage of AADT(Cars) to AADT(Total), and the broad linear relationship of traffic and residential prices which was confirmed in the machine learning section through gradient descent on a large dataset which gives the observation credibility.
